Posted: Thu May 03, 2012 5:35 am
I have been accepted to the University of Virginia. They have a remote learning program for Engineering Science, specializing in EE/ME/Materials. My specialization would be Mechatronics. While their traditional Engineering programs are ABET accredited, this one is not, and likely will not be, as confirmed by the Director of the program. Now, what kind of risk am I taking if I go down this road and end up with a non-ABET degree? I live in SE Virginia, big Navy area, but there are lots of other employers as well.
sowellfan
Ars Praefectus
et Subscriptor
Registered: Mar 8, 2002Posts: 3765
Posted: Thu May 03, 2012 11:59 am
Well, I guess the first question is, "Do you want to be an engineer?" Obviously if you want to get a PE license at some point, then this isn't the school for you. But I think lots of other places that hire "engineers", even without the PE license requirement, would balk at the non-ABET accreditation.On the other hand, if you're looking to work in some sort of field where you're not expected to be an engineer, but maybe more of a robotics/electronics guru, it might be reasonable to stay in that program.What sort of places are you thinking about working?
sowellfan
Ars Praefectus
et Subscriptor
Registered: Mar 8, 2002Posts: 3765
Posted: Thu May 03, 2012 12:10 pm
On looking at the website for that program, I'm kind of horrified that it's so hard to find the accreditation information. I mean, I know that the guy told you that the program isn't accredited, but I was wondering which of their engineering programs *are* - and I couldn't even find that. Best I could do was one blurb next to the list of undergrad engineering programs (of which there are 10 or more) saying that they have 9 accredited programs. What a crappy way of disseminating information.
