Posted: Thu May 03, 2012 3:27 pm
I have a little bit of experience in this actually. My degree is basically an engineering degree without the engineering accreditation and a slightly different class makeup.As has been said if you want a job with the title ME, EE, CE, etc. or want to get you PE, you will want to be in an accredited program.The lack of engineering accreditation did not significantly effect me because I have never really worked as an engineer. My career started in embedded systems software development in the late 1980's. My education was geared towards this, but it was not something you could get a degree in back in the 1980's. So while employers would have liked an engineering degree, they were just happy to get someone that knew what assembly language was, much less the fact that I used the exact same processor and development tools in school.I have since moved on to working in IT as a Administrator/DBA/Programmer where my schooling has little to do with the work I do.I have seen the lack of an accredited engineering degree adversely effect others however. Not so much in getting into some place, but in the ability to advance. I have seen a couple people passed over for positions with the word engineer in the title, even though they could design circles around the engineer that was hired.So think seriously about what kind of career and advancement opportunities you want. If you are going to be a "maker" working for yourself or working some start up the exact degree is not a big deal. If you want to work for a more traditional company and move up through the engineering ranks the degree and accreditation will make a difference.
Kaiser Sosei
