I would not recommend doing a degree in Engineering Science/Physics unless you were 120% sure you were ready to commit to either a masters/PhD in a more traditional engineering field (at least by name, you'll be able to direct the study more to your liking) or a law degree looking to do patent law.
nugzboltz
Ars Praetorian
Registered: Aug 31, 2007Posts: 429
Posted: Mon May 07, 2012 9:05 am
I've been applying for a bunch of federal jobs lately (as a environmental engineer), and most jobs have had this standard degree requirement (check out http://www.usajobs.gov or for that matter any corporate website if you want to check out random job requirements):"A. Degree: professional engineering. To be acceptable, the curriculum must: (1) be in a school of engineering with at least one curriculum accredited by the Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology (ABET) as a professional engineering curriculum; or (2) include differential and integral calculus and courses (more advanced than first-year physics and chemistry) in five of the following seven areas of engineering science or physics: (a) statics, dynamics; (b) strength of materials (stress-strain relationships); (c) fluid mechanics, hydraulics; (d) thermodynamics; (e) electrical fields and circuits; (f) nature and properties of materials (relating particle and aggregate structure to properties); and (g) any other comparable area of fundamental engineering science or physics, such as optics, heat transfer, soil mechanics, or electronics."So going with a non-ABET degree means that you'll still have doors open, but you have to be cognizant of the fact that it is going to close a lot of them too, as you won't be able to get a PE, which a lot of private sector engineering firms want you to be able to obtain within 2 years or so of you starting to work there.
