Posted: Tue May 08, 2012 7:06 am
Looking at the website linked by the OP, and their Engineering Science page, this program seems to be an odd hybrid of basic core from community college classes, followed by a "double minor" of proper engineering courses from UVA, with some added specialization and a senior thesis-type project. While I kind of see what they're going for, and I think you could do just fine in a career based on that coursework, I don't actually see much advantage to be had there relative to what could be achieved within a conventional e.g. mechanical engineering program with appropriately-selected electives, and possibly a community-college transfer process if those cost vs. time tradeoffs were appealing. Honestly the ABET accreditation process has always been a bit unclear to me. At my school the mechanical engineering degree had for decades been listed as a B.S. in "Engineering and Applied Science" with a concentration in mechanical engineering. This program was accredited. My senior year, they reshuffled some stuff in the course catalog and created a B.S. in Mechanical Engineering, with the same coursework requirements as the previous program. This is the degree I received. However, since it was the first year of the program, technically the ABET accreditation process had not been completed at the time I received my degree... but maybe there's some kind of retroactive accreditation granted? I'm sure I could argue it successfully if it was challenged, but I've never been completely confident where it stands.As far as the PE licensing goes, the vast majority of the mechanical engineers I've worked with do not have one, and I don't really see a need for it in most trajectories I can see my career taking... though I would like to go through the process and get the license one of these years, just for its own sake. On the other hand, my wife works at a civil engineering consulting company, and with her Environmental Science degrees she has been hampered in advancement somewhat, because of the way PE licensure is baked into the company's advancement policies and employee grade-level descriptions. Not all companies are like that, but it's a concern worth keeping in mind.
