Posted: Tue May 08, 2012 7:50 am
PsionEdge wrote:I did a little looking into info about the PE and basically since the licensing is regulated at the state level if you work on products that could be sold across state lines a PE license is not required. So it makes sense that the only people that seem to need them are those working civil engineering projects and construction sites/buildings..It sounds like you're convinced that you're not going into an industry that requires one, but this isn't entirely correct; you are indeed licensed by a state, but since everybody takes the same tests administered by the NCEES, nearly every state has reciprocity (I've also heard them called "comity") agreements with every other state. Thus you get licensed in state A and for a fee and a chunk of verification data, you can get a license in states B, C, and D as well. Thus we have old guys with licenses from seven different states on their wall (this mainly applies to the old onshore guys, as offshore design just requires a stamp from the state in which your firm is registered)./end derailFor whatever it is worth, I'd second the advice calling for an ABET accredited degree; I interned at a defense contractor and was told "lol, PE?" time and again, but ended up in a different industry (I'm an ME). Just because you don't need one now doesn't mean you never will (particularly in a boom/bust industry like defense traditionally is).
